Here's the standard approach:

### 1. Define each theme as a `ResourceDictionary`

```xml
<!-- Resources/Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
                    x:Class="MyApp.Resources.Themes.LightTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

Create matching `DarkTheme.xaml` and `HighContrastTheme.xaml` with different color values.

### 2. Create a theme service

```csharp
public enum AppTheme { Light, Dark, HighContrast }

public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;
        mergedDicts.Clear();

        mergedDicts.Add(theme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Dark         => new Resources.Themes.DarkTheme(),
            AppTheme.HighContrast => new Resources.Themes.HighContrastTheme(),
            _                     => new Resources.Themes.LightTheme(),
        });

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", theme.ToString());
    }

    public static AppTheme GetSavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", nameof(AppTheme.Light));
        return Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(saved, out var t) ? t : AppTheme.Light;
    }
}
```

### 3. Apply the saved theme at startup

In `App.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(ThemeService.GetSavedTheme());
}
```

### 4. Build the settings page picker

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" Title="Theme"
        ItemsSource="{Binding Themes}"
        SelectedItem="{Binding SelectedTheme}"
        SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged" />
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object? sender, EventArgs e)
{
    if (ThemePicker.SelectedItem is AppTheme selected)
        ThemeService.ApplyTheme(selected);
}
```

### 5. Reference theme keys with `DynamicResource`

This is **critical** — `StaticResource` won't update at runtime:

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label Text="Hello" TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryText}" />
    <Button BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource AccentColor}" />
</ContentPage>
```

### Key points

- **`DynamicResource`** everywhere you use a themed key — it re-evaluates when the dictionary changes.
- **`Preferences`** persists the user's choice across launches.
- **`MergedDictionaries.Clear()` + `Add()`** swaps the active theme instantly, no restart needed.
- Keep your resource keys consistent across all three XAML files so every `DynamicResource` resolves in every theme.
